        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>High Data Rate: The number of spectral windows is based on 1) fulfilling the primary goals of imaging 1 H2CO and multiple CH3OH lines, and 2) imaging or detecting 4 other molecules of high astrochemical interest. Furthermore, at the proposed rms the line density of disks is unknown and maximizing the bandwidth is important to maximize the chances of serendipitous line discoveries. It is key that the number of requested spectral windows and their resolution is kept to maximize the science outcome of this project. 

Requested sensitivity: The sensitivity request is based on the expected image requirements of H2CO around the CO snowline, where we need to be able to detect signal constrasts on the order of 10 mJy. Fortuitously a similar sensitivity is required to obtain the first detection of CH3OH in a disk if it is coforming with H2CO. For a 5sigma H2CO contrast and a 5sigma CH3Oh detection we therefore request a rms of 2 mJy per 1 km/s (the line width).

Imaging requirements: To image the H2CO and CH3OH  spatial distribution with respect to the TW Hya 30 AU (0.5")  snow line, we require a resolution of 0.5". We Used the Cycle 2 configuration (5), which results in synthesized beam of 0.5", to simulate observations with CASA Simobserve() and this resulted in that all flux from the skymodels is recovered. No ACA is therefore required.

Correlator setup: Band 6 is optimal to image organics in disks when considering both the intrinsic line strengths and the expected low excitation temperatures of organics in disks -- the estimated excitation temperature of H2CO in TW Hya is &lt;17K (Qi, Oberg et al. 2013a). The primary frequency windows are selected to cover the most intense CH3OH lines in band 6, the J=5-4 ladder around 241.8 GHz, and the H2CO J=3_{0,3}-2_{0,2} line at 225.698 GHz. Additional windows are placed on CN 2-1, HDO, c-C3H2 and SO2. The requested frequency resolution for the high-priority lines corresponds to ~0.17 km/s will enable detailed velocity structure modeling. For the lower priority lines we request a resolution of 0.3 km/s to barely resolve the lines while simultaneously obtaining continuum data.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
